In article <1992Apr28.031255.5011@microsoft.com> erich@microsoft.com (Eric Hanchrow) writes:
>I've gotten the impression that the ``one-time pad'' encryption scheme
>is genuinely unbreakable (albeit too inconvenient for the real world).
>I want to know if there's a proof that it's unbreakable.

Any message of the same length can encrypt to the same result using an
appropriately chosen pad.  There's nothing to choose between all these
messages unless you have the pad.

Of course, this depends on the numbers being truly random.  And you
mustn't use the same set twice.

